    <h1>omniguard Privacy Policy</h1>
    <p class="updated">Last updated: 2026-04-17</p>

    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      omniguard is a browser extension that simulates and explains blockchain transactions before
      you sign them in your wallet. It highlights asset changes, approval changes, permission
      changes, and potential risks.
    </p>

    <h2>Data Collection</h2>
    <p>
      omniguard does <strong>not</strong> sell personal data, run ad tracking, or include
      analytics SDKs. It sends transaction payloads to the configured simulation API so the
      transaction can be analyzed before signing.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>No account information</strong>: The extension does not require you to create an
        account or provide any personal information.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No browsing history</strong>: The extension does not track your browsing activity
        outside of transaction interception.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No analytics or tracking</strong>: The extension does not include any analytics,
        telemetry, or tracking SDKs.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Data Processing</h2>
    <p>
      The extension processes the following data locally and/or through a user-configured API
      endpoint:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Transaction parameters</strong>: When you initiate a transaction on a DApp (via
        <code>eth_sendTransaction</code> or <code>eth_signTransaction</code>), the extension
        captures the transaction parameters (<code>from</code>, <code>to</code>,
        <code>value</code>, <code>data</code>, <code>chainId</code>) to send them for simulation
        analysis.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Analysis results</strong>: Simulation results (asset changes, approvals,
        permissions, risk assessment) are received from the API and displayed in the extension
        popup and overlay.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>API Communication</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        By default, the extension communicates with the hosted simulation API at
        <code>https://trace-parser-2a3u6jbsja-as.a.run.app</code>.
      </li>
      <li>Users can configure a custom API URL through the extension settings.</li>
      <li>
        The API endpoint determines where transaction payloads are processed for simulation. The
        default endpoint is operated for the extension's transaction-analysis purpose.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Permissions Explanation</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>activeTab</strong>: Required to interact with the current tab when analyzing transactions.</li>
      <li><strong>storage</strong>: Used to save the user's API URL configuration locally.</li>
      <li><strong>tabs</strong>: Required to send analysis results to the correct browser tab.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>host_permissions (&lt;all_urls&gt;)</strong>: Required to intercept wallet
        transaction requests on any DApp website. This is necessary because DApps can be hosted on
        any domain.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Data Storage</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The extension uses <code>chrome.storage.local</code> to store the API URL, UI language
        preference, install ID, and temporary API credentials returned by the simulation service
        bootstrap flow.
      </li>
      <li>
        Transaction data and analysis results are kept in memory only and are cleared when the tab
        is closed or navigated away.
      </li>
      <li>
        No wallet private keys, seed phrases, or browsing-history archives are stored by the
        extension.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Third-Party Services</h2>
    <p>
      The extension does not integrate with any third-party services, advertising networks, or data
      brokers.
    </p>

    <h2>Children's Privacy</h2>
    <p>This extension is not directed at children under 13 years of age.</p>

    <h2>Changes to This Policy</h2>
    <p>
      We may update this privacy policy from time to time. Changes will be reflected in the
      "Last updated" date above.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      If you have questions about this privacy policy, please open an issue on the project's GitHub
      repository.
    </p>
